<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TITLE -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Overview / Getting Started
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        An overview of the Prim Editor layout, required directories, model loading workflow, and 3D viewport controls.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- OVERVIEW -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What the Prim Editor Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Prim Editor is used to view, create, edit, texture, import, and export Urban Chaos
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.PRM</Run>
        objects. These objects are used by the game for many placed models, such as street lamps,
        signs, bins, crates, small scenery objects, pickups, trees, and other world details.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The editor supports two main workflows. You can build a simple object directly in the editor
        by placing points and forming triangle or quad faces, or you can import a model from another
        3D tool such as Blender using the
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.OBJ</Run>
        format. The Prim Editor is then used to assign game textures, configure UV regions, set
        object flags, and save the result back to a game prim slot.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_overview_full_window.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- MAIN LAYOUT -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Main Interface Layout
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The Prim Editor is arranged around the 3D viewport. The surrounding panels are used to load
        models, select textures, edit object properties, and manage face data.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Status bar</Bold> — shown at the bottom of the window. It displays useful
                information such as loaded directories, model counts, current status messages, and
                file operation results.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>File menu</Bold> — located at the top. This contains commands for creating,
                saving, importing, and exporting PRM and OBJ files.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Quick action buttons</Bold> — located underneath the menu. These provide fast
                access to common commands such as New, Import OBJ, Save As PRM, and Export OBJ.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Edit bar</Bold> — located below the quick actions. This controls the current
                editing mode, such as selection mode, add point mode, new triangle mode, and new quad
                mode.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>File explorer</Bold> — located on the left. This is where you set the game
                prim directory and browse existing PRM files.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Textures panel</Bold> — located along the bottom. This displays the available
                prim texture library and the UV region preview for the selected face.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Prim information panel</Bold> — located on the right. This contains model
                properties, face material information, object flags, collision settings, damage
                settings, and shadow settings.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>3D viewport</Bold> — located in the centre. This is where the model is viewed,
                rotated, inspected, and edited.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Start by loading the texture directory first. Many existing PRMs will appear untextured
                    or confusing until the correct TGA texture library has been loaded.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- TEXTURE DIRECTORY -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Step 1: Set the Texture Directory
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Before loading or texturing PRM objects, set the texture directory. This tells the Prim
        Editor where to find the
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.TGA</Run>
        files used by prim objects. These texture files are normally stored in the shared prim
        texture directory.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For a standard GOG installation, the directory is usually:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
C:\Program Files (x86)\GOG Galaxy\Games\Urban Chaos\server\textures\shared\prims
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        To set this directory, click the <Bold>Set Texture Dir</Bold> button in the Textures panel.
        A folder selection dialog opens. Browse to the folder above, select it, and confirm.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Once the directory is selected, the texture library loads all available TGA files from that
        folder. These textures can then be applied to individual prim faces.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_overview_set_texture_dir.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- PRIM DIRECTORY -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Step 2: Set the Game Prim Directory
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The game prim directory contains the existing PRM files used by Urban Chaos. Setting this
        directory allows the editor to discover and list the available prims. It is also the normal
        location where custom PRM files are saved when you want the game to use them.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For a standard GOG installation, this directory is usually:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
C:\Program Files (x86)\GOG Galaxy\Games\Urban Chaos\server\prims
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        Click <Bold>Set Directory</Bold> in the File Explorer panel and select the
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">server\prims</Run>
        folder. Once set, the file explorer populates with discovered PRM files. Selecting one of
        these entries loads that prim into the viewport.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_overview_set_prim_dir.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- STARTING OPTIONS -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        After the Directories Are Set
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Once both directories are configured, you can choose one of three workflows:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Create a new PRM from scratch</Bold> by selecting
                <Bold>File → New</Bold>, pressing the <Bold>New</Bold> quick action button, or using
                <Bold>Ctrl+N</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Edit an existing PRM</Bold> by selecting it from the file explorer on the left.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Import an OBJ model</Bold> from a modelling tool such as Blender, then assign
                textures and PRM-specific game properties inside the Prim Editor.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,8,0,0">
        The built-in modelling tools are deliberately basic. They are useful for simple objects,
        small fixes, and low-poly construction. For more complex shapes, it is usually better to
        build the model in Blender or another 3D editor and then import the finished mesh as OBJ.
    </Paragraph>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- NAVIGATION -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Navigating the 3D Viewport
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The 3D viewport is used to inspect the model, place points, select faces, and confirm
        texturing. The control hints are shown in the viewport information box.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>W</Bold> — move forward.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>S</Bold> — move backward.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>A</Bold> — strafe left.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>D</Bold> — strafe right.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Q</Bold> — lower the camera.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>E</Bold> — raise the camera.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>[</Bold> and <Bold>]</Bold> — rotate around the model.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>'</Bold> and <Bold>.</Bold> — change pitch.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Right-click and drag</Bold> — rotate the view around the model.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Mouse wheel</Bold> — zoom in and out.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>R</Bold> — reset the view.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosPrimEditor;component/Help/Images/prim_overview_3d_navigation.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Recommended first test:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Set the texture directory, set the PRM directory, load an existing object, rotate around it,
                    select a face, and inspect the UV region before attempting to create a new model.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
